  passages: [
    {
      title: "The Fox and the Drought",
      text: "For many weeks not a single drop of rain had fallen. The river shrank to a trickle, and the ground grew hard and cracked. All the forest animals grew thin and thirsty, for the drought had stolen their water away.\nOne cunning old fox refused to give up. He had noticed that the ants always marched toward one shady corner beneath the ancient oak. \"Ants are never far from water,\" he thought. So he followed them, digging where they vanished into the earth. Deep down, cool and hidden, he found a spring still bubbling. The fox shared the secret with the other animals, and though the drought lasted many more days, not one creature went thirsty again.",
      questions: [
        { q: "The fox followed the ants because he reasoned that 'ants are never far from water.' What kind of thinking did this show?", o: ["He used a clue to work out where water was", "He was lucky by accident", "He was afraid of the ants", "He wanted to eat the ants"], a: 0, s: true },
        { q: "The story says the drought 'had stolen their water away.' What is a drought?", o: ["A long time with no rain", "A sudden flood", "A cold winter", "A strong wind"], a: 0 },
        { q: "How do we KNOW the spring the fox found was worth sharing?", o: ["No creature went thirsty again", "The ants left the forest", "The river filled at once", "The rain returned that day"], a: 0, s: true },
        { q: "The fox is called 'cunning'. Using the whole story, 'cunning' here most nearly means ________.", o: ["cleverly able to work things out", "large and strong", "gentle and shy", "lazy and slow"], a: 0, s: true },
        { q: "Why is it a little surprising that tiny ANTS helped save the big animals?", o: ["Small creatures gave the clue the big ones missed", "Ants can carry water for animals", "Ants are bigger than foxes", "The animals asked the ants for help"], a: 0 },
        { q: "What is the BEST lesson this story teaches?", o: ["Watching closely and thinking can solve hard problems", "Foxes dislike ants", "Rain always returns quickly", "Rivers never run dry"], a: 0 }
      ]
    },
    {
      title: "The Reluctant Painter",
      text: "Duc could draw better than anyone in his class, but he refused to enter the school art contest. \"What if my painting is not good enough?\" he whispered. His teacher did not scold him. Instead, she quietly hung one of his old sketches on the wall without telling him.\nThe next morning, a crowd of students stood before the sketch, astonished. \"Who made this? It is magnificent!\" they said. Duc listened from the back, his cheeks warm. That afternoon, without a word to anyone, he took out his paints and began the finest picture he had ever made. He entered the contest after all — and though he did not win first place, he was no longer afraid to show his work.",
      questions: [
        { q: "At the start, WHY was Duc reluctant to enter the contest?", o: ["He feared his work was not good enough", "He could not draw at all", "He had no paints", "The contest was cancelled"], a: 0, s: true },
        { q: "The teacher hung his sketch up WITHOUT telling him. Why was this a clever plan?", o: ["He heard honest praise he could believe", "It hid his work from everyone", "It won the contest for him", "It made the students leave"], a: 0, s: true },
        { q: "The students were 'astonished' by the sketch. This tells us they were ________.", o: ["very surprised and impressed", "bored and tired", "afraid of it", "unable to see it"], a: 0 },
        { q: "'His cheeks warm' as he listened. What feeling does this most likely show?", o: ["Shy pride at being praised", "Anger at the crowd", "Cold from the weather", "Hunger for lunch"], a: 0, s: true },
        { q: "How do we know Duc had CHANGED by the end of the story?", o: ["He entered the contest even though he had refused before", "He stopped painting forever", "He won first place easily", "He moved to a new class"], a: 0 },
        { q: "Duc 'did not win first place' but the story still ends happily. Why?", o: ["He beat his own fear of showing his work", "First place did not matter to anyone", "He was given a prize anyway", "The other painters all left"], a: 0 }
      ]
    },
    {
      title: "The Translucent Egg",
      text: "Deep in the tall grass, Mai found a small egg that glowed a soft, translucent green when she held it up to the sun. She did not know what it was, so she made a cosy nest of leaves and kept it warm each day, though her brother laughed and called it a useless stone.\nWeeks passed. One quiet morning the egg trembled, then cracked, and out wriggled a tiny lizard with delicate, jewel-bright scales. It blinked at Mai as if it already knew her. \"See?\" Mai said gently to her astonished brother. \"Patience is never wasted.\" From that day the little lizard followed Mai everywhere, and her brother never called anything useless again.",
      questions: [
        { q: "The egg was 'translucent'. From the story, 'translucent' means ________.", o: ["letting soft light pass through", "made of hard stone", "painted bright green", "very heavy"], a: 0, s: true },
        { q: "Mai's brother called the egg a 'useless stone.' How do we know he was WRONG?", o: ["A living lizard hatched from it", "It turned into a real stone", "Mai threw it away", "It never changed at all"], a: 0, s: true },
        { q: "Why did Mai keep the egg WARM every day?", o: ["Eggs need warmth for the baby inside to grow", "To make it change colour", "To hide it from her brother", "To cook it slowly"], a: 0 },
        { q: "The lizard 'blinked at Mai as if it already knew her.' Why might it seem to know her?", o: ["She had cared for its egg all along", "They had met before it hatched", "Lizards can read minds", "Her brother told it about her"], a: 0, s: true },
        { q: "Mai says, 'Patience is never wasted.' What does she mean by this?", o: ["Waiting carefully can lead to good things", "Eggs are a waste of time", "Lizards are impatient", "Brothers are always right"], a: 0 },
        { q: "How did the brother CHANGE from the beginning to the end?", o: ["He stopped calling things useless", "He took the lizard for himself", "He learned to make nests", "He laughed even louder"], a: 0 }
      ]
    }
